tegrouporder":"1","sortid":"5","short_tag":"India","article_id":"2410854","post_title":"When inclusion means respecting my disability, I feel empowered","post_content_stripped":"This International Week of the Deaf, we’re putting the spotlight on our very own Ajeesh Thulaseedharan, who shares how our culture of equality has enabled him to grow professionally and personally.  Disabled but not labelled Born deaf, communicating with people was never easy. So, I am always open and honest about my disability to avoid misunderstandings. This is especially important for not immediately visible or hidden disabilities, like mine. When I joined Accenture in 2012, I initially had some challenges. I remember, once, someone called me from a couple of meters behind in the cafeteria and I did not react – for the simple reason that I was unable to hear my name being called. Similarly, it had happened that I missed a funny remark during a meeting. But, since I had let my team know about my disability they never labelled me as being non-humorous or impolite. You, me and the culture of equality! From the outset, I was impressed with Accenture’s positive approach as they tried to concentrate on what skills I could offer as opposed to seeing me being deaf as a barrier. And, this support has been continuous over the years. In these eight years, I have worked with four different teams and had two promotions. I started off as a contractor and today, I am a permanent employee, working in the Claims Processing team. My colleagues have never hesitated in including me in any of the team activities and events. They even showed interest in learning the sign language which I was eager to train them in.  And gradually, things fell in place for all of us. I would especially like to thank my manager, who always supported and encouraged me to go the extra mile. “Communication is always a challenge for people like me. So, I always wanted to create a device to convert voice into subtitles during calls. And, now with our latest AI-enabled Dhvani app, I see we are headed in that direction. Looking forward to using it soon.” Dhvani is a step ahead in creating accessible communication to empower our deaf and speech-disabled colleagues by converting speech to text and text to speech. To download and know more about the app, click here. Surprise, surprise! I love travelling. You would be surprised to know that I have travelled almost all of India except four places. I am so in love with the beauty of Taj Mahal that I have visited the place 38 times. In fact, my colleagues joke that I should do ‘work from Taj.’ I have also guided many hearing-impaired foreign tourists in their travel expeditions. That was an enriching experience for me as I learnt a lot from them about their countries as well. Accenture is also ensuring an inclusive, accessible, barrier-free work environment to support our people. Our new Adjustment Request Tool on Service Now is a personalized platform to empower our special needs colleagues. Requests for place accommodation, for assistive technology, workplace adjustments and transportation arrangements can be placed in just a few clicks now!","post_excerpt":"","post_content":"<style type=\"text/css\"><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span> h1.ih-entry-title{font-weight:700; text-transform: uppercase; font-size:52px; letter-spacing:-1px; color:#7500cc;} .disability p, .disability em{line-height:25px; font-size:17px;} .disability h6{font-weight:700 !important; font-size: 22px; text-transform: uppercase; margin-bottom:0; color:#7500cc;} .disability a{color:#008eff; text-decoration:underline !important;} .comSec{border:2px dashed #a100ff; padding:15px 15px 0; border-radius:25px; margin-bottom:20px;}</style>\r\n<div class=\"disability\">\r\n\r\n<em>This International Week of the Deaf, we’re putting the spotlight on our very own </em><a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/a.a.thulaseedharan\"><strong><em>Ajeesh Thulaseedharan</em></strong></a>,<em> who shares how our culture of equality has enabled him to grow professionally and personally.</em><em> </em>\r\n<h6>Disabled but not labelled</h6>\r\nBorn deaf, communicating with people was never easy. So, I am always open and honest about my disability to avoid misunderstandings. This is especially important for not immediately visible or hidden disabilities, like mine.\r\n\r\nWhen I joined Accenture in 2012, I initially had some challenges. I remember, once, someone called me from a couple of meters behind in the cafeteria and I did not react – for the simple reason that I was unable to hear my name being called. Similarly, it had happened that I missed a funny remark during a meeting. But, since I had let my team know about my disability they never labelled me as being non-humorous or impolite.\r\n<h6>You, me and the culture of equality!</h6>\r\nFrom the outset, I was impressed with Accenture’s positive approach as they tried to concentrate on what skills I could offer as opposed to seeing me being deaf as a barrier. And, this support has been continuous over the years. In these eight years, I have worked with four different teams and had two promotions. I started off as a contractor and today, I am a permanent employee, working in the Claims Processing team.\r\n\r\nMy colleagues have never hesitated in including me in any of the team activities and events. They even showed interest in learning the sign language which I was eager to train them in.  And gradually, things fell in place for all of us. I would especially like to thank my manager, who always supported and encouraged me to go the extra mile.\r\n<div class=\"comSec\">\r\n\r\n“Communication is always a challenge for people like me. So, I always wanted to create a device to convert voice into subtitles during calls. And, now with our latest AI-enabled Dhvani app, I see we are headed in that direction. Looking forward to using it soon.”\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://dhvani.accenture.com/home\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>Dhvani</strong> </a>is a step ahead in creating accessible communication to empower our deaf and speech-disabled colleagues by converting speech to text and text to speech.\r\n\r\nTo download and know more about the app, <a href=\"https://dhvani.accenture.com/home\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>click here</strong></a>.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h6>Surprise, surprise!</h6>\r\nI love travelling. You would be surprised to know that I have travelled almost all of India except four places. I am so in love with the beauty of Taj Mahal that I have visited the place 38 times. In fact, my colleagues joke that I should do ‘work from Taj.’\r\n\r\nI have also guided many hearing-impaired foreign tourists in their travel expeditions. That was an enriching experience for me as I learnt a lot from them about their countries as well.\r\n\r\n<img src=\"https://in.accenture.com/india/wp-content/uploads/sites/548/2020/09/Gallery.jpg\" alt=\"\" />\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<style type=\"text/css\"><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span> h1.ih-entry-title{color: #460073;font-weight:600;} .inclusive h4{font-family: Graphik Black;color: #000;font-size: 24px;display:initial;} p.suHeading{font-size:22px;letter-spacing: -0.1px;margin-bottom:6px;font-family:Graphik Black;margin-top:20px;color:#a100ff;} .watch iframe{border-top:33px solid #000;width:750px;} .textWithBand{background: #a100ff;margin-bottom: 30px;font-weight:600;}  div.callOut{border-top:4px solid #a100ff;border-bottom: 4px solid #a100ff;padding:10px;width:100%; margin-bottom:20px;} .signUp ul{list-style:none;margin:0;padding:0;background:#7500c0;transition:all 0.7s !important;} .signUp ul li{display:block;color:#fff;margin-bottom:4px;transition: all 0.7s;border-bottom