oClose]=true&amp;flashvars[chapters.plugin]=true&amp;flashvars[chapters.layout]=vertical&amp;flashvars[chapters.thumbnailRotator]=false&amp;flashvars[streamSelector.plugin]=true&amp;flashvars[EmbedPlayer.SpinnerTarget]=videoHolder&amp;flashvars[dualScreen.plugin]=true&amp;\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>","post_link":"https://in.accenture.com/india/?site=1&blog=548&p=4723","site_url":"https://in.accenture.com/india/","post_thumb":"https://cdn.in.accenture.com/prod/wp-content/uploads/sites/548/2017/09/05092935/Lalithashree-Gangadharaiah.jpg","post_date":"2017-09-06 04:33:05","post_modified":"2020-10-05 09:29:59","isread":"0","article_score":"50.154632","isfeatured":"1","source_short_tag":"India","category_url":"https://in.accenture.com/india/","source_url":"https://in.accenture.com/india"},{"aggregator_short_tag":"Location","aggmeta_short_tag":"Location","aggregator_siteid":"169","aggregatorunreadcount":"77","sitegrouporder":"2","sortid":"8","short_tag":"India","article_id":"2448456","post_title":"What are your stress signals?","post_content_stripped":"﻿﻿﻿﻿﻿﻿﻿﻿ Everyone feels stress, but not all stress is created equal. Positive stress, like when we’re working hard on a passion project and near the finish line, can actually boost performance and increase energy. Negative stress, on the other hand, can have the opposite effect — draining our energy, impacting our productivity and even affecting our personal relationships. We all experience negative thought patterns or emotions from time to time, and that’s completely normal. It’s critical that we recognize those patterns so we can take steps to better manage our stress before we become stuck in a negative loop. Know your stress signals Using cutting-edge research from Stanford Medicine, Thriving Mind explores eight different ways that negative stress expresses itself — called biotypes. Understanding your biotype can help you identify your own personal signs of stress and empower you to take meaningful action in your everyday life. What are the eight biotypes? Rumination Rumination is characterized by overanalyzing situations, constant worrying and dwelling on negative thoughts, which can result in feeling paralyzed and worthless. Threat Response After facing a threat-related event, our brain returns back to its usual baseline. But when you’re in an extreme form of fight or flight, you may find yourself stuck in alarm mode and unable to recover. Negative Bias Our brain is naturally wired to react more quickly to negative information than to positive, but typically, our brain resolves those negative reactions right away. Negative Bias happens when the negative reactions persist and are reinforced through behaviors like negative self-talk, seeking constant reassurance, or apologizing excessively. Anxious Avoidance People who identify with Anxious Avoidance may exhibit distressed behavior, avoid social situations, spend more time alone, and may have a severe aversion to changes around them. Cognitive Fog Going through a period of constant stress can leave our brain feeling foggy, rather than sharp. People who identify with this biotype may have difficulty articulating thoughts or language, or experience forgetfulness. It can be hard to execute decisions, plan ahead, and implement tasks at work and home. Inattention With Inattention, your capacity to sustain focus and attention over time is disrupted. Basic functions at work and home may feel extremely difficult or impossible, and it can be exhausting to force yourself to concentrate on the task at hand. Emotional Numbness People who identify with this biotype may not be able to find pleasure in the things they normally enjoy. They may feel empty, have a hard time identifying purpose, or feel like they’re going through the motions. Some people with this biotype may turn to food or alcohol in an attempt to feel any emotion at all. Context Insensitivity Context Insensitivity is a form of Emotional Numbness, where the brain loses the capacity to find one thing more motivating or important than the other. When Context Insensitivity develops, the brain is on the verge of complete burnout and people may find it hard to function at work or in relationships. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Start the Thriving Mind course to learn more about biotypes and the recharge strategies you can adopt to calm better manage your negative stress.   Available resources Employee Assistance Programs are available in 100% of our operating countries, free of charge to all employees. Find the EAP program in your country. Mental Health Ally programs are available in more than 30 countries with more than 6,500 trained employees. Find a mental health ally near you. ********** The Thriving Mind course is intended to provide a general education and awareness about preventative measures that can improve your mental well-being. The course is not a substitute for professional medical advice, diagnosis, or treatment. If you have or think you have any signs, symptoms or concerns related to mental wellness, please seek professional help through your health care provider or Accenture’s Employee Assistance Program.","post_excerpt":"Thriving Mind explores eight different ways that negative stress expresses itself — called biotypes. Understanding your biotype can help you identify your own personal signs of stress and empower you to take meaningful action in your everyday life.","post_content":"<iframe src=\"https://thriveglobal.touchcast.com/s/oneejmaw4i\" width=\"640\" height=\"404\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-bl