w.accenture.com/us-en/insights/cloud/ascend-to-cloud\"><strong>“Cloud is the urgent business imperative: How to maximize its value”</strong></a></em></span>, which marks the beginning of our Cloud Acceleration campaign. This campaign will drive consideration of Accenture as the premiere partner for cloud migration, and how we are uniquely able to remove risk through our industry, business and cloud knowledge.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline; color: #851cdd;\"><a style=\"color: #851cdd; text-decoration: underline;\" href=\"https://in.accenture.com/sellingaccenturetechnology/?site=1&amp;blog=46&amp;p=21830&amp;caturl=aHR0cHM6Ly9pbi5hY2NlbnR1cmUuY29tL3NlbGxpbmdhY2NlbnR1cmV0ZWNobm9sb2d5L2NhdGVnb3JpZXMtbmV3cy8=\">Read more →</a></span>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://collections.accenture.com/collection.aspx?b=cbd9cc6c-ee20-ea11-8186-0a360102099e\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-25339\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenturetechnology/wp-content/uploads/sites/46/2020/09/IES09292020-048.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"580\" height=\"400\" /></a>\r\n\r\nCopyright 2020 Accenture.\r\nAll rights reserved. <img class=\"wp-image-20707 alignright\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenturetechnology/wp-content/uploads/sites/46/2020/04/Accenture-logo.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"161\" height=\"36\" />","post_link":"https://in.accenture.com/accenturetechnology/?site=1&blog=46&p=25291","site_url":"https://in.accenture.com/accenturetechnology/categories-news/","post_thumb":null,"post_date":"2020-09-29 17:23:53","post_modified":"2020-09-30 15:08:37","isread":"0","article_score":"212.227025","isfeatured":"0","source_short_tag":"Accenture Technology","category_url":"https://in.accenture.com/accenturetechnology/categories-news/","source_url":"https://in.accenture.com/accenturetechnology"},{"aggregator_short_tag":"Global","aggmeta_short_tag":"Global","aggregator_siteid":"598","aggregatorunreadcount":"11","sitegrouporder":"4","sortid":"19","short_tag":"Across Accenture","article_id":"2383438","post_title":"We bridge the gap between disability and potential","post_content_stripped":"Not many of us express joy at yet another meeting. But for Darianne Darjuan, App/Cloud Support Associate, being able to fully participate in a meeting is a welcome change. “I sometimes find it hard to keep up in meetings, especially if someone is talking fast, because of my hearing disability,” she explains. But with the establishment of our Accessibility Center in the Philippines, Darianne is one of 600+ employees who now has best-fit assistive technologies at their disposal. The center, meant to drive inclusion in the workplace, allows her to perform to her potential with a little digital help. Accenture Labs developed a solution called Dhvani, which means “sound” in Hindi. Here, artificial intelligence (AI) translates spoken words into text in real time. Using Microsoft Cognitive Services,  the solution allows people with hearing and speech impairments to participate in video calls, listen to webcasts and converse with coworkers. “I am thankful I am able to use Dhvani,” says Darianne. “This helps me keep up in meetings. I can now take calls, provide input, and understand what other people are saying.” The center is filled with similar solutions meant to help employees with disabilities, like Drishti, an AI-powered solution to help visually impaired people. Drishti means “vision” in Sanskrit; it uses smartphones to describe the environment around a visually impaired person, using: image recognition natural language processing natural language generation The ripple effect We’ve also been able to provide more than 4,100 team members with disability-prevention technologies like blue-light-filter glasses and anti-fatigue mats, creating a base model for the entire process to be replicated at Accenture locations worldwide. It’s working. In December, 2019, we launched similar centers in China, India, Japan and Malaysia. And we’re helping 17 additional countries do the same. “There’s no secret to creating accessibility and inclusion,” says Rudy Guiao, Accessibility Center lead and Infrastructure Services lead for ASEAN/Greater China. “It’s entirely possible when you are focused on the goal. But this project reflects the passion and purpose of our Infrastructure Services team. Intent on creating a barrier-free workplace, we have a dedicated team responsible for continuous research and development of assistive technology offerings. All of our Accessibility Center architects continually learn and upskill to keep the team relevant in this space.” “An innovation for a greater purpose” Inside of Accenture, the team’s work has been recognized with a Greater Than Award, but its positive impact extends outside of Accenture also. Several clients, including Google, Microsoft, Newmont and Sensis, are considering opening accessibility centers after seeing our positive results. “Creating the disability center was an eye opener,” says Paul Paglinawan, network operations engineer. “A key realization for all of us was that persons with disabilities all have different and unique needs, so we had to keep discovering and offering a wide range of solutions. For example, one kind of headset was not suitable for all hearing  impairments.” Rudy says the team appreciates that winning a Greater Than Award means more people at Accenture will be aware of the possibilities for people with disabilities. “Aside from the global recognition, GTA opens a bigger platform for our advocacy to be promoted and adapted by all of Accenture. It’s humanizing technology translated to an innovation for a greater purpose.” That greater purpose spans the globe. More than one billion people live with some form of disability. That’s one in seven of us. And 80% of them acquire their disability during their working years, between the ages of 18 and 64. As a result, they are 50% more likely to be unemployed. We’ve put a dent in that statistic with our accessibility centers. And with Accenture operations in 17 more countries looking to be more progressive in this area, we hope to see that 50% decrease at an increasing rate. Not only is that good for our people, it’s good for our business. Our Getting to Equal: The Disability Inclusion Advantage research shows that more inclusive companies are twice as likely to have higher total shareholder returns than their peers, on average. Plus, companies that have become more inclusive over time are four times more likely to have total shareholder returns that outperform those of their peer group. When it comes to profitability and value creation, these companies achieved 28% higher revenue, double the net income and 30% higher economic profit margins over the four-year period we analyzed, on average. Kudos to the team Congrats to the entire Accessibility Center Team for their hard work, passion and purpose. It certainly shows in the final result. Rudy Guiao, team lead Ella Vinuya Paul Ranjan Claudette Laurence Dionisio Paul Gemar Paglinawan Joan Liston Estrelle Falsis Darwin Polendey Vida Grace Luad Katrina Farcon Surendra Seshagiri Tony Leraris Janna Berkholz Yuri Iskandar Rajkumar Sharma Xiaofeng Jiang Kazuto Saito Shoko Ohwada Jennifer Joyce Abella Thomas Neil Wagan Gitanjali Krishnan Diogenes Rulloda Francis Crisostomo Mary Joyce Mejia Neil Davadilla Alexei Dacanay","post_excerpt":"The Accessibility Center in the Philippines won the 2020 Company and People Greater Than Award for using best-fit assistive technologies to drive inclusion in the workplace.","post_content":"<iframe id=\"kmsembed-0_d73lewh4\" class=\"kmsembed\" title=\"Kaltura Player\" src=\"https://mediaexchange.accenture.com/embed/secure/iframe/entryId/0_d73lewh4/uiConfId/27188232\" width=\"608\" height=\"456\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>\r\nNot many of us express joy at yet another meeting. But for <a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/darianne.l.b.darjuan\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Darianne Darjuan</a>, App/Cloud Support Associate, being able to fully participate in a meeting is a welcome change. “I sometimes find it hard to keep up in meetings, especially if someone is talking fast, because of my hearing disability,” she explains.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://ideas.accenture.com/35ADFBA0-C7F8-4E48-8B30-C4F6500C228D/101297\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-7114\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/wp-content/uploads/sites/290/2020/09/CALLOUT_GTA-company-people.png\" alt=\"Winner of an FY20 Company &amp; People Greater Than Award!\" width=\"325\" height=\"120\" /></a>But with the establishment of our <a href=\"https://mediaexchange.accenture.com/media/0_d73lewh4\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Accessibility Center</a> in the Philippines, Darianne is one of 600+ employees who now has best-fit assistive technologies at their disposal. The center, meant to drive inclusion in the workplace, allows her to perform to her potential with a little digital help.\r\n\r\nAccenture Labs developed a solution called <a href=\"https://www.accenture.com/us-en/blogs/blogs-disability-inclusion-next-workplace-frontier\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Dhvani</a>, which means “sound” in Hindi. Here, artificial intelligence (AI) translates spoken words into text in real time. Using Microsoft Cognitive Services,  the solution allows people with hearing and speech impairments to participate in video calls, listen to webcasts and converse with coworkers.\r\n\r\n“I am thankful I am able to use Dhvani,” says Darianne. “This helps me keep up in meetings. I can now take calls, provide input, and understand what other people are saying.”\r\n\r\nThe center is filled with similar solutions meant to help employees with disabilities, like <a href=\"https://newsroom.accenture.com/news/accenture-develops-artificial-intelligence-powered-solution-to-help-improve-how-visually-impaired-people-live-and-work.htm?_ga=2.252290112.898237939.1598553140-2043022064.1539883806&amp;_gac=1.89861609.1595870947.CjwKCAjw9vn4BRBaEiwAh0muDKI8RItgmitflGSOkTzbGIWv9xAcHz-pbOUZ3yQty7qVvawEr2ckIxoCb9UQAvD_BwE\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Drishti</a>, an AI-powered solution to help visually impaired people. Drishti means “vision” in Sanskrit; it uses smartphones to describe the environment around a visually impaired person, using:\r\n<ul>\r\n \t<li>image recognition</li>\r\n \t<li>natural language processing</li>\r\n \t<li>natural language generation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2><strong>The ripple effect</strong></h2>\r\n<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-7116\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/wp-content/uploads/sites/290/2020/09/CALLOUT_billion-disability.png\" alt=\"CALLOUT: More than one billion people in the world live with some form of disability — one in seven of us. \" width=\"325\" height=\"160\" />We’ve also been able to provide more than 4,100 team members with disability-prevention technologies like blue-light-filter glasses and anti-fatigue mats, creating a base model for the entire process to be replicated at Accenture locations worldwide.\r\n\r\nIt’s working. In December, 2019, we launched similar centers in China, India, Japan and Malaysia. And we’re helping 17 additional countries do the same.\r\n\r\n“There’s no secret to creating accessibility and inclusion,” says <a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/rudy.p.guiao.jr\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Rudy Guiao</a>, Accessibility Center lead and Infrastructure Services lead for ASEAN/Greater China. “It’s entirely possible when you are focused on the goal. But this project reflects the passion and purpose of our Infrastructure Services team. Intent on creating a barrier-free workplace, we have a dedicated team responsible for continuous research and development of assistive technology offerings. All of our Accessibility Center architects continually learn and upskill to keep the team relevant in this space.”\r\n<h2><strong>“An innovation for a greater purpose”</strong></h2>\r\nInside of Accenture, the team’s work has been recognized with a <a href=\"https://ideas.accenture.com/35ADFBA0-C7F8-4E48-8B30-C4F6500C228D/101297\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Greater Than Award</a>, but its positive impact extends outside of Accenture also. Several clients, including Google, Microsoft, Newmont and Sensis, are considering opening accessibility centers after seeing our positive results.\r\n\r\n“Creating the disability center was an eye opener,” says <a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/paul.g.r.paglinawan\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Paul Paglinawan</a>, network operations engineer. “A key realization for all of us was that persons with disabilities all have different and unique needs, so we had to keep discovering and offering a wide range of solutions. For example, one kind of headset was not suitable for all hearing  impairments.”\r\n\r\nRudy says the team appreciates that winning a Greater Than Award means more people at Accenture will be aware of the possibilities for people with disabilities. “Aside from the global recognition, GTA opens a bigger platform for our advocacy to be promoted and adapted by all of Accenture. It’s humanizing technology translated to an innovation for a greater purpose.”\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-7115\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/wp-content/uploads/sites/290/2020/09/CALLOUT_accessibility-and-inclusion.png\" alt=\"CALLOUT: &quot;There’s no secret to creating accessibility and inclusion. It’s entirely possible when you are focused on the goal.&quot;\" width=\"325\" height=\"186\" />That greater purpose spans the globe. More than <a href=\"https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2019/04/what-companies-gain-including-persons-disabilities-inclusion/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">one billion people</a> live with some form of disability. That’s one in seven of us. And 80% of them acquire their disability during their working years, between the ages of 18 and 64. As a result, they are 50% more likely to be unemployed.\r\n\r\nWe’ve put a dent in that statistic with our accessibility centers. And with Accenture operations in 17 more countries looking to be more progressive in this area, we hope to see that 50% decrease at an increasing rate.\r\n\r\nNot only is that good for our people, it’s good for our business. Our <a href=\"https://www.accenture.com/us-en/about/inclusion-diversity/persons-with-disabilities\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Getting to Equal: The Disability Inclusion Advantage</a> research shows that more inclusive companies are twice as likely to have higher total shareholder returns than their peers, on average. Plus, companies that have become more inclusive over time are four times more likely to have total shareholder returns that outperform those of their peer group. When it comes to profitability and value creation, these companies achieved 28% higher revenue, double the net income and 30% higher economic profit margins over the four-year period we analyzed, on average.\r\n<h2><strong>Kudos to the team</strong></h2>\r\nCongrats to the entire Accessibility Center Team for their hard work, passion and purpose. It certainly shows in the final result.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-7134\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/wp-content/uploads/sites/290/2020/09/meet-the-accessibility-center-team.png\" alt=\"two group portraits of many people\" width=\"281\" height=\"355\" />\r\n<ul>\r\n \t<li><a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/rudy.p.guiao.jr\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Rudy Guiao</a>, team lead</li>\r\n \t<li><a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/pamela.ann.r.vinuya\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Ella Vinuya</a></li>\r\n \t