ce_url":"https://in.accenture.com/accenture"},{"aggregator_short_tag":"Global","aggmeta_short_tag":"Global","aggregator_siteid":"598","aggregatorunreadcount":"11","sitegrouporder":"4","sortid":"20","short_tag":"Across Accenture","article_id":"2402340","post_title":"We’re helping Joe Depa keep a promise to his daughter","post_content_stripped":"Raising funds for cancer research and counseling families of a child battling cancer is all part of a promise Joe Depa made to his three-year-old daughter Melissa, who died from leukemia five years ago — and one that the Accenture Applied Intelligence team is helping him keep. “When I learned that Melissa was going to pass away, I told her I was sorry that I couldn’t stop it from happening, but I made a promise that I was going to keep fighting for her and other children,” Joe says. He and his wife Erika continue to make good on that promise, raising more than $700,000 for cancer causes since 2015 through United for a Cure, which they founded in Melissa’s memory. And every year on Melissa's birthday they and their two sons collect and donate 1,000 toys to the hospital. Joe also serves on the board of directors of Cure Childhood Cancer, an Atlanta-based nonprofit organization, and is a trained mentor for families of children with cancer in association with St. Jude’s Children’s Research Hospital. “Research shows that unless you have walked in the shoes of a parent who has lost a child, it is very hard to relate,” Joe says. “My heart is scarred and that will never go away. But every time I’m able to help people through their pain it’s like a band-aid for the soul.” What Joe learned from that tragedy has affected the work he does in Accenture. “This experience really changed me as leader,” he says. “I have become more compassionate, as everyone has something they are going through in life. It is important to be there for each other and realize we are all in this together.” Accenture helps with data and analytics Accenture was affected too. When our leaders in the United States learned of Joe’s tireless efforts, we joined his cancer research cause. Our contribution is a data and analytics approach, developed in collaboration with researchers and clinicians from Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center (Fred Hutch), one of the largest pediatric cancer centers in the world, and the Target Pediatric AML computational working group, a large-scale research project that supplied the data. Developed by our data scientists, the approach aims to help pediatric oncology physicians and researchers better analyze patient genetic data to potentially advance precision medicine. “When Joe asked our Applied Intelligence team to be a part of his quest to find a cure for childhood cancer, it was an enthusiastic yes,” says Jimmy Etheredge, chief executive officer for North America. “By helping Joe keep his promise to Melissa, we are also making good on our company’s mission to improve the way the world works and lives. All of Accenture can be proud of the work we’ve done — and we thank Joe and his family for all they’ve done in their daughter’s name.” Joe, Applied Intelligence lead for the U.S. South Market Unit, says that our data scientists who worked with Fred Hutch had the clinical and genomic background knowledge to hit the ground running and truly make a difference. He notes that treatment of leukemia is not a one-size-fits-all approach, as cures usually involve using a variety of different medications and treatments and most patients respond differently. “The good news is that treatments are advancing, and our company is at the forefront of the effort,” Joe says. “I’m hopeful there will be a cure for leukemia and childhood cancer in our lifetime.” Photo caption: Joe with Melissa and mom Erika. More information Read the news release on accenture.com Contact joseph.depa@accenture.com","post_excerpt":"Raising funds for cancer research and counseling families of a child battling cancer is all part of a promise Joe Depa made to his three-year-old daughter Melissa, who died from leukemia five years ago.","post_content":"Raising funds for cancer research and counseling families of a child battling cancer is all part of a promise <a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/joseph.depa\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Joe Depa</a> made to his three-year-old daughter Melissa, who died from leukemia five years ago — and one that the Accenture Applied Intelligence team is helping him keep.\r\n\r\n“When I learned that Melissa was going to pass away, I told her I was sorry that I couldn’t stop it from happening, but I made a promise that I was going to keep fighting for her and other children,” Joe says.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.accenture.com/us-en/blogs/blogs-careers/honoring-my-daughter-and-fighting-childhood-cancer-at-accenture\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-7112\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/wp-content/uploads/sites/290/2020/09/CALLOUT_share-this-outside-the-company.png\" alt=\"CALLOUT: Share this story with your contacts outside the company.\" width=\"325\" height=\"121\" /></a>He and his wife Erika continue to make good on that promise, raising more than $700,000 for cancer causes since 2015 through <a href=\"https://curechildhoodcancer.org/about-cure/named-funds/united-for-a-cure/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">United for a Cure</a>, which they founded in Melissa’s memory. And every year on Melissa's birthday they and their two sons collect and donate 1,000 toys to the hospital.\r\n\r\nJoe also serves on the board of directors of <a href=\"https://curechildhoodcancer.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Cure Childhood Cancer</a>, an Atlanta-based nonprofit organization, and is a trained mentor for families of children with cancer in association with St. Jude’s Children’s Research Hospital.\r\n\r\n“Research shows that unless you have walked in the shoes of a parent who has lost a child, it is very hard to relate,” Joe says. “My heart is scarred and that will never go away. But every time I’m able to help people through their pain it’s like a band-aid for the soul.”\r\n\r\nWhat Joe learned from that tragedy has affected the work he does in Accenture.\r\n\r\n“This experience really changed me as leader,” he says. “I have become more compassionate, as everyone has something they are going through in life. It is important to be there for each other and realize we are all in this together.”\r\n<h2><strong>Accenture helps with data and analytics</strong></h2>\r\nAccenture was affected too. When our leaders in the United States learned of Joe’s tireless efforts, we joined his cancer research cause.\r\n\r\nOur contribution is a data and analytics approach, developed in collaboration with researchers and clinicians from <a href=\"https://www.fredhutch.org/en.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center</a> (Fred Hutch), one of the largest pediatric cancer centers in the world, and the <a href=\"https://targetpediatricaml.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Target Pediatric AML</a> computational working group, a large-scale research project that supplied the data.\r\n\r\nDeveloped by our data scientists, the approach aims to help pediatric oncology physicians and researchers better analyze patient genetic data to potentially advance precision medicine.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-6964 alignright\" src=\"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/wp-content/uploads/sites/290/2020/09/joedepa_callout2.png\" alt=\"Callout: “Every time I’m able to help people through their pain it’s like a band-aid for the soul.”\" width=\"325\" height=\"145\" />“When Joe asked our Applied Intelligence team to be a part of his quest to find a cure for childhood cancer, it was an enthusiastic yes,” says <a href=\"https://people.accenture.com/People/user/james.o.etheredge\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Jimmy Etheredge</a>, chief executive officer for North America. “By helping Joe keep his promise to Melissa, we are also making good on our company’s mission to improve the way the world works and lives. All of Accenture can be proud of the work we’ve done — and we thank Joe and his family for all they’ve done in their daughter’s name.”\r\n\r\nJoe, Applied Intelligence lead for the U.S. South Market Unit, says that our data scientists who worked with Fred Hutch had the clinical and genomic background knowledge to hit the ground running and truly make a difference. He notes that treatment of leukemia is not a one-size-fits-all approach, as cures usually involve using a variety of different medications and treatments and most patients respond differently.\r\n\r\n“The good news is that treatments are advancing, and our company is at the forefront of the effort,” Joe says. “I’m hopeful there will be a cure for leukemia and childhood cancer in our lifetime.”\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 8pt;\"><strong>Photo caption:</strong> Joe with Melissa and mom Erika.</span>\r\n<h2><strong>More information</strong></h2>\r\n<a href=\"https://newsroom.accenture.com/news/accenture-puts-data-science-to-work-for-pediatric-leukemia-research.htm\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Read the news release on accenture.com</a>\r\n<h2><strong>Contact</strong></h2>\r\n<a href=\"mailto:joseph.depa@accenture.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">joseph.depa@accenture.com</a>","post_link":"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/?site=1&blog=290&p=6959","site_url":"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/","post_thumb":"https://cdn.in.accenture.com/prod/wp-content/uploads/sites/290/2020/09/30212119/Joe-Melissa-Erika-Depa_800x480.jpg","post_date":"2020-09-28 01:00:01","post_modified":"2020-09-30 21:22:04","isread":"0","article_score":"212.449346","isfeatured":"1","source_short_tag":"Across Accenture","category_url":"https://in.accenture.com/accenture/","source_url":"https://in.a