udwig van Beethoven was deaf. Like one billion people alive today, each of them had a disability and it didn’t stop them from making amazing contributions — just like many of our Accenture people do every day. Everyone at Accenture has unique skills, talents and strengths to contribute. Through our commitment to disability inclusion, we are working to break down barriers and create an accessible, inclusive work environment, so that all persons with disabilities can share their talents to help drive innovation, power business performance and create a true sense of belonging. “Disability inclusion is really personal for me, and I’m proud of the work that we’re doing,” said CEO Julie Sweet. “In my volunteer work during college and former pro bono work as a lawyer, I saw firsthand the challenges people with disabilities face, and it opened my eyes to the critical need for disability inclusion. It provides opportunities that are great for our people, our culture, our innovation and our growth. At Accenture, we’re setting goals, we have an action plan and are measuring our progress, but we’ve got much more to do.” Technology makes accessibility possible Technology plays a powerful role in providing more access to persons with disabilities, and we’re taking steps to ensure that all Accenture people with disabilities are equipped with the tools, technologies and accommodations they need to be successful. “When you think about the power of technology to provide more access for individuals with disabilities, you really see the idea of delivering on the promise of technology come to life,” said Julie. “When we design disability inclusion into technology, we are breaking down barriers to inclusivity.” Your commitment to disability inclusion You also play an important role in disability inclusion by taking steps to make your content accessible to as many people as possible. The Accessibility Guide showcases ways that we can adopt simple actions to make our content accessible. From running the accessibility checker tool before sending an email, to including alternative text to describe an image, to captioning videos before posting — we all have the power at our fingertips to make our work more accessible for persons with disabilities. Visit the Accessibility Guide for more simple tips on how you can “Think Accessible” and be a part of the movement to create a barrier-free workplace for everyone. Want to do more to help? Explore the links below to learn how you can help build an inclusive culture for persons with disabilities. Learn more about disability inclusion and our other available resources. Watch Julie Sweet and Chad Jerdee discuss the importance of disability inclusion. Subscribe to the Global Inclusion &amp; Diversity site to read the latest disability inclusion news and personal stories.","post_excerpt":"Through our commitment to disability inclusion, we are working to break down barriers and create an accessible, inclusive work environment, so that all persons with disabilities can share their talents to help drive innovation, strong business performance and create a true sense of belonging.","post_content":"<iframe id=\"kmsembed-0_gjmzagq4\" class=\"kmsembed\" title=\"Kaltura Player\" src=\"https://mediaexchange.accenture.com/embed/secure/iframe/entryId/0_gjmzagq4/uiConfId/27188232\" width=\"608\" height=\"386\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_start\">﻿</span><span data-mce-type=\"bookmark\" style=\"display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;\" class=\"mce_SELRES_st